Hard Time Linux
Title
Making Linux do
Hard (Real-)Time
Deus ex Machina
Simulated Time systems compute time like any other internal variable
They contain a model of their virtual world
Picture of computer in feedback loop with another containing a globe
Any system that interacts with the real, physical world
Obviously, almost all systems operate in real-time
Picture of computer in feedback loop with a Globe
Time is an external input
Real-Time deadlines can be
hard: where missed deadline means system failure
characteristic of interactions with physical world
firm: occasional missed deadlines are tolerable
characteristic of interactions with other computers
soft: preceived "quality" of system degrades as deadlines are missed
characteristic of interactions with humans
These are overgeneralizations
Most systems have multiple deadline types, each with unique qualities.
The devil is in the details.
A system is denoted as hard, firm or soft Real-Time depending on its
most challenging deadlines.
"Hard-realtime" systems may have firm and/or soft deadlines as well
Computers are fast relative to most real-time constraints
Embededed Linux is everywhere!
It is inexpensive, robust, easy to program,
hosts a huge number of languages and libraries
Simply dedicate sufficient computing resources to ensure
hard real-time deadlines are always met.
Picture of utopian fantasy
Linux was designed to be open, flexible, fair, and fast.
It was never intended to meet hard real-time deadlines.
Long running Linux kernel operations could not be interrupted.
Device Drivers would occaisionally disable interrupts for many milliseconds.
These issues were scattered throughout the kernel sources!
Linux systems typically utilize large, multi-layer memory caches
These caches dramatically improve throughput (ie. average speed)
But they slow performance on cache misses
The time taken to complete the same computation can vary by
orders of magnitude depending on history and other system loads.
Sometimes the best course is to disable some aspects of caching
Such as "locking down" a real-time process in physical memory
Hard Real-Time processes cannot reliably utilize more than a small
fraction of the available compute power on a general purpose Linux box.
Graph depicting wildly varying compute times for a repitivive task
with deadlines being occasionally missed as a result.
Caching degrades deterministic response
Turning caching off indescriminately kills throughput
and can lead to fatal Out of Memory Errors
The PREEMPT_RT patch dramatically reduces the kernel's max. latency
--> a truely amazing feat of software engineering!!
But, the RT patch is still not in the kernel mainline, because:
It lowers aggregate throughput
Some low-end platforms lack the hardware support to implement RT well.
Device drivers have been steadily improved
Picture of Linux cereal box, reveals "Now with Real-Timetm"
Modern, popular programming environments and languages
Often sacrifice determinism for ease of use
May "automagically" invoke time-consuming algorithms.
Software Libraries are black boxes by design
APIs specify inputs and outputs, but rarely compute time.
Applications with challanging hard timing deadlines are often forced to
utilize low-level programming and to reimplement existing libraries.
Our cerebral cortex is analogous to the typical Linux computer
It is very complex, flexible, and, sometimes, even fair.
It, too, struggles to do real-time control well.
Yet, we are blessfully unaware of firing of individual muscles for
walking, talking, eating, digestion, etc.
Routine activities are controled by our periphral nervous system
Our cerebrum focuses on analysing and responding to unusual stimuli
at a high level.
Our cerebellum, or "little brain", coordinates stimulation with motion
it is our center for real-time control and preception
One can survive removal of one's cerebellum, but:
the resulting quality of life is significantly compromised
with clumsiness, ...,
slowing of various cognitive perceptual processes, and
impaired fine motor and ocular-motor coordination.
http://jcn.sagepub.com/content/17/1/1.abstract
Identify what event-response loops have the most demanding deadlines
Factor only these critical loops into a separate, streamlined executable(s)
This is your "Cerebellum"
Implement it in a system programming language (like 'C' or C++)
Minimize use of 3rd-party libraries
Connect it to your main application
Now your are ready to...
Depict cotrol loop being pulled out of hairball of logic
Run your real-time event response loops on reserved computing resources
Initally, try using virtual computing resources
Linux processes with Real-Time priority
Most convenient option
This is not very effective without an RT-patched kernel
Use fast, native IPC mechanisms for communication with main app
Allows complete access to Linux kernel and user space
But the more you access Linux, the more you risk priority inversion
Separate real-time tasks running with Linux in a hypervisor environment
Less convenient
Works quite well even without an RT-patched kernel
Use hypervisor specific IPC mechanisms for comms with main app
Does not allow easy access to Linux kernel and user space
No danger of priority inversion
http://wiki.ok-labs.com/
Dedicate microcontrollers to your critical event-response loops
The least "convenient" option, but offering:
No requirement for a RT-patched Linux kernel
Much more deterministic response times
Microcontrollers have little or no caching
No resource contention
Much lower power consumption
Ability to safely limp or shutdown if host computer crashes
Diagram of Distributed Control with Linux host at its hub
Microcontrollers are cheap and many use the GNU Compiler Collection
Including support for remote target debugging
Some even support hardware floating point
Picture of STM32 microcontroller for $11
Disadvantages:
Custom hardware design
Generally a lot slower than most x86 systems
No Interprocess Communication
Must use some form of physical networking
If you need specialized I/O
You can likely find a microcontroller that already incorporates it.
Many USB I/O extenders are just such microcontrollers
Programmed to provide bit-level access to their built-in peripherals
But, with custom programming, they can do much more!
